-------> Scripture

Before getting into Matthew chapter 3, let's do a quick recap of key events in chapter 2:

When Jesus was around 2 years old, wise men (Maji) followed a star to bethlehem to worship the young child and bring gifts

Joseph is warned by an angel in a dream to fleewith jesus and Mary to egypt to escape King herod who wants to kill the child

Herod kills all male children of 2 years or less in Bethlehem, hoping to kill Jesus

After Herod dies, an angel tells Joseph to return. Fearing Herods son Archelaus, the family returns to Galilee and settles in Nazareth 


As we move from Chapter 2 to 3 theres a huge jump forward in time

Matthew doesn't report anything in the life of Jesus between when Joseph settled in Nazareth to the current time where Jesus encounters John the baptist where 25-30 years have passed (not the same John who wrote the gospel of John)

John is actually the cousin of Jesus, only around 6 months apart in age

In his gospel, Luke tells the story of how John was a miracle child, born to Zecheriah and Elizabeth who were thought to be too old to have children and both descendants of the priestly line of Levites

Luke also spoke of the important role John would play in preparing the way for Jesus

Luke says that before John was born, an angel told his father about the man John would become

The angel said that John would turn many of the children of Israel to God and to make ready for the Lord a people prepared


Lets read the word starting with verse 1-6

--> READ verse 1-6

So Matthew introduces John as a preacher in the wilderness of Judea which was a dry, rough land near the dead sea

So John wasn't in a heavily populated or high traffic area. His location meant that people who wanted to listen had to come to him

John was known as the baptist or baptizer because baptizing people was a sign of their repentance from sin and that was a foundational element of John's ministry

John's first words are "repent, for the kingdom of heaven is at hand"

The word "repent" is Metanoeite in Greek which means "to change one's mind and heart"

More literally, it means to change direction, to stop going the wrong way and to start going in the right way. 

So repent isn't just the feeling of being sorry for one's sins, conveys an active change. 

By asking people to repent, John was calling the people of Israel to confess their sins and submit to God

Jewish people at that time would have been aware of a new kingdom that would one day come via the promised messiah

By saying the kingdom of heaven is at hand, John is expressing that the kingdom isn't a distant thing, but that its as close as your hand

John proclaims Jesus as the messiah and therefore the kingdom is iminent, not distant

He's saying with urgency that repentance for sin is needed for people to be included in the kingdom and that mere inclusion in Jewish heritage isn't sufficient

In verse 3 Matthew connects John to the prophecy in Isaiah 40:3 which says "A voice cries: In the wilderness prepare the way of the Lord, make straight in the desert a highway for our God"

With this reference, Matthew is showing that this verse in Iasaiah relates to John the Baptist preparing the way for Jesus

John's role was to "clear the path" for Jesus by calling people to repent for their sins and turn back to the way of God. if people did that, they would be ready to follow God's son

In verse 4 Matthew talks about John wearing a garment of camel hair, a leather belt and eating locusts and wild honey. This would have been typical clothing of wild nomads

Even though John was of priestly lineage, he chose a simple life in the wilderness, wearing clothes and eating food that normal, poorer people would be wearing and eating. 

In verse 5 emphasizes that despite him being in the wilderness people travelled from Jerusalem and all around Judea to come witness John, hear his words and be baptized by him

Verse 5 repeats the word all twice. Says all Judea and all the region about the Jordan. Repeated to emphasize that many people were coming to see John, not just a few

John's message was simple and potent

The kingdom of heaven is near. The Messiah is coming. Confess and repent of your sins. Demonstrate your commitment to leading a holy life by being baptized

John's baptism was one of clensing and declaring agreement with God. It was a public declaration of a renewed commitment to live as God commanded

John's baptism of repentance which is different than the symbolism of modern day Christian baptism which in part symbolizes ones death and resurrection with Christ


--> READ verse 7-8

People coming to see John preaching in the wilderness attracted the attention of religious leaders of Israel who were known as Pharisees and Sudducees who didn't like each other

Pharisees were religious teachers and leaders connected to common people and engaged at the local synagogue level

They held themselves to strict standards when it came to adhering to the law. They also developed a system of rules that went beyond the law of Moses

The Sadducees were a much smaller group of wealthier priests and religious aristocrats. 

They were known for their cooperation with Rome's occupation and were resented by the people


They come to see what John is up to and when John sees them, he calls them a brood of vipers. Snakes. He connects them with the deceiving serpent in the garden of Eden. Strong accusation

He then asks them who told warned them to flee from God's incoming wrath

His words show that he views the religious leaders of Israel as sinful and unrepentant

He then tells them to prove by how they live that they have repented for their sins and oriented themselves to God


--> READ verses 9-10

John warns the religious leaders that Gods coming judgement will be upon them

John reminds them that just because they are children of Abraham as Israelites, it doesnt preclude them from judgement

He warns them not to presume incorrectly that they won't be judged because of who they are because judgment will be based on how they act

He says that God can raise up new children of Abrahamfrom stones if that is required

Through Jesus, new children will be added to the line of Abraham

In verse 10 John is saying that every tree that does not bear good fruit. Every person that does not behave righteously

Will feel the axe (aka judgement) of God and be cut down and thrown into fire

Those who do not bear good fruit by leading lives that are holy and faithful to God will be pruned from the tree. Deleted from the lineage. Thrown into the fire as dead branches


--> READ verses 11-12

Here John makes it clear that he is not the messiah and his baptism is not the same as the one coming after him (Jesus)

John makes reference to the divine status of Jesus by saying he isn't even worthy of carrying his sandals. In those times, only the most lowly servant would carry sandals and John says he's not even worthy to carry Jesus' sandals

He reiturates that his baptism of repentance is very different than the baptism being given by the coming Messiah which will be by the Holy Spirit and fire

John mentions that Jesus will wield a winnowing fork as a metaphor for judgement

A winnowing fork would separate the valuable wheat from the worthless chaff which would then be blown away by the wind

Those who repent and follow Christ are the wheat while the Chaff symbolizes those who reject Christ

John is saying that unbelievers will burn in unquenchable fire


--> READ 13-15

Matthew now introduces the main character, Jesus, for the first time as an adult

Jesus finds John preaching and baptizing in the wilderness and asks him to baptize him

John is suprised by the request. He doesn't even feel worthy of carrying his sandals let alone baptize Jesus

He also knew that Jesus has no sin to repent of so baptism didn't make sense for Jesus

Jesus insists that John baptizes him, saying "it is fitting for [them] to fulfill all righteousness."

Sounds like Jesus is saying "you should baptize me because it's what God wants" and then John agrees to it


--> READ 16-17

Jesus' baptism gets an immediate response from the father

As Jesus emerges from the water, the heavens open up and Jesus sees the Holy Spirit as a dove descending onto him 

This sign made for a powerful confirmation that Jesus was being empowered by God

As if it wasn't clear enough, the people who were present hear the voice of God saying "This is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased."

In this moment, it becomes very clear that Jesus is the son of God

In this moment, all 3 parts of the trinity are present

God the Son, in human form who is joined by God the Holy Spirit in dove-like form, while the voice of God the Father calls down from heaven.



Summary of chapter 3: 

Matthew introduces a unique character of the new testament: John the baptist

John was related to Jesus. He was Jesus' cousin, born only around 6 months apart

He was a miracle child born to Zacharias and Elizabeth, a couple that was thought to be too old to have children

John is introduced as a man preaching in the Judean wilderness, clothed in camel hair and eating honey and locusts. His purpose is to prepare the way for Jesus

John is telling people to repent for the kingdom of heaven is near. Meaning, Christ is coming and judgement is at hand. as close as our hand

John rebukes the Jewish leaders of the day for coming to be baptized without authentic repentance. He warns that those not producing good fruit will be cut down and thrown into fire

He talks about his baptism of reptenace and the incoming baptism by Jesus with either the Holy Spirit or fire

Jesus then visits John and is baptized which signifies the commmencement of his ministry

During Jesus' baptism, he receives a divine endorsement from God himself. 





